    ARTICLE

    Dynamic Programming for the Time-Dependent Traveling Salesman Problem with Time Windows

    View article page
    Gonzalo Lera-Romero, Juan José Miranda Bront and Francisco J. Soulignac

    Abstract

    The time-dependent traveling salesman problem with time windows (TDTSPTW) is a variant of the well-known traveling salesman problem with time windows, in which travel times are not assumed to be constant. The TDTSPTW accounts for the effects of congestion at the planning level, being particularly suited for distribution problems in large cities. In this paper we develop a labeling-based algorithm for the TDTSPTW that incorporates partial dominance and generalizes several state-of-the-art components from the time-independent related literature. We propose a framework general enough to be applied to the TDTSPTW and its variant without time windows, with the objective of minimizing the duration or the makespan. As part of the framework, we introduce a new state-space relaxation specifically designed for the time-dependent context. Extensive computational experiments show the effectiveness of the overall approach and the impact of the new relaxation, outperforming several recent algorithms proposed for these variants on more than 9,000 benchmark instances. In addition, we frame the minimum tour duration problem within the time-dependent literature and include it as a benchmark for our algorithm, obtaining improved computation times and 31 new optimal solutions.

    Summary of Contribution: In this paper, we study the time-dependent traveling salesman problem with time windows (TDTSPTW), a difficult single-vehicle routing problem that incorporates more realistic travel time functions than its classic time-independent counterpart. As a result, the TDTSPTW is harder to solve, as it requires more complex models and algorithms. Using state-of-the-art optimization techniques, we propose an efficient solution approach for the TDTSPTW and some related variants that outperforms the previous approaches in the literature. Our paper emphasizes the importance of algorithmic design and efficient implementations to tackle relevant practical combinatorial optimization problems—in particular, for time-dependent problems. Moreover, the resulting algorithm fosters a new research direction regarding exact algorithms for time-dependent problems using dynamic programming and relaxation techniques.

1. Introduction
The recent growth of direct-to-consumer deliveries
has stressed the importance of last-mile logistics,
becoming one of the critical factors in city planning.
According to different studies, one of the key factors
lies in the last-mile deliveries, reaching in some cases
nearly 50% of the overall parcel delivery cost (see, e.g.,
Joerss et al. (2016) and Savelsbergh and Van Woensel
(2016)). Variants of the traveling salesman problem (TSP)
arise naturally at the core of complex decision-making
processes within last-mile logistics. Among them, one
of the most relevant is the TSP with time windows
(TSPTW), in which each customer must be visited
within a speciﬁc time interval. When restricting to dis-
tribution problems in large cities, the congestion of the
road network is another key aspect with a signiﬁcant
practical impact. Accounting effectively for the effects
of congestion at the planning level results in more

accurate distributions plans; neglecting its impact can
lead to infeasible routes violating the time windows.
The time-dependent TSPTW (TDTSPTW) is a general-
ization of the TSPTW that models congestion by not
assuming that the travel time between two customers
remains constant over the planning horizon.
Given a digraph D  (V, A) with vertices V  {0,
1, : : : , n + 1}, the TDTSPTW ﬁnds a route from 0 to n +
1 that passes through every vertex in V exactly once.
Vertices 0 and n + 1 represent a starting and ending
depot, respectively, whereas V\{0, n + 1} represents a
set of customers. The route is traversed by a single
vehicle whose operations take place within a planning
horizon [0, T]. Associated with each v ∈ V is a time
interval [av, bv] ⊆ [0, T] that speciﬁes the time window in
which the service of v must begin. The vehicle can
arrive to a vertex v before its release av, but it must
wait until av to start the service. Upon completion of
the service, the vehicle departs to the next vertex in the
tour. For each (v, w) ∈ A, the time required to travel
from v to w is given by a travel time function τvw. That
is, for each t ∈ [0, T], τvw(t) is the time spent by the
vehicle to travel from v to w when it leaves v at time t.
The TDTSPTW applies the travel time model pro-
posed by Ichoua et al. (2003), in which each τvw is
continuous, piecewise linear, and satisﬁes the ﬁrst-in,
ﬁrst-out (FIFO) property (see Section 3).
As in the TSPTW, some instances could be infeasible,
meaning that it might not be possible to ﬁnd a route vis-
iting all the vertices exactly once within their time win-
dow. Deciding whether an instance is feasible or not is
an N P-complete problem (see, e.g., Ascheuer et al.
(2000)). Given a feasible instance, the TDTSPTW ﬁnds a
feasible route of minimum duration—that is, a route
that minimizes the time it takes for the vehicle to leave 0
until it reaches n + 1. The TDTSPTW generalizes several
single-vehicle routing problems, four of which are of
interest in this article. The TDTSP (without time win-
dows) is obtained by letting [0, T] be the time window
of every vertex for a large enough T. The makespan ver-
sions of the TDTSPTW and the TDTSP follow when
a0  b0  0 (i.e., when the vehicle is forced to leave the
depot as early as possible). By the FIFO property, these
problems minimize the time in which the vehicle
returns to the end depot. These versions are called
the TDTSPTWm and the TDTSPm, respectively. Finally,
the minimum tour duration problem (MTDP) is the
time-independent version of the TDTSPTW, and it is
obtained when τvw is a constant function for every arc
(v, w) ∈ A. To complete the whole picture, the TSPTW in
which travel costs are given by travel times (TSPTWm)
can be interpreted as the makespan version of the MTDP;
that is, the departure time from the depot is not a deci-
sion variable. Thus, the TSPTWm is obtained from the
MTDP when a0  b0  0. The duration versions of these
problems are much harder than their makespan coun-
terparts, because the departure of the vehicle from the
depot 0 can be deferred to reduce the duration of the
route. That is, the duration of a route is a function
depending on the arrival time.
1.1. Motivation
The current state-of-the-art algorithms to exactly solve
the TDTSPTW, the TDTSPTWm, and the TDTSPm rely on
integer linear programming. By contrast, the most effec-
tive algorithms developed for their time-independent
counterparts, such as the TSPTW, develop sophisticated
frameworks based on dynamic programming (DP). In
this regard, two successful algorithms are proposed by
Baldacci et al. (2012) for the TSPTW and Tilk and Irnich
(2017) for the MTDP, which showed to be very effective
within their domains. In a nutshell, the framework is the
following: ﬁrst apply a penalty method on a heavily
relaxed problem, then dynamically compute the ng
neighborhoods on less relaxed problems, and ﬁnally
solve the exact problem applying completion bounds
computed on the last relaxation solved.
In the exact step, Baldacci et al. (2012) used the
lower bound lb of the last relaxation to guess an upper
bound ub  1:01lb. Assuming the guess is correct, com-
pletion bounds are applied to discard labels. In case of
failure, a new guess is attempted, potentially recom-
puting labels from the previous iterations. This algo-
rithm works well because lb is sufﬁciently tight in the
TSPTW; thus few guesses of ub are required. Tilk and
Irnich (2017) implement this idea for the MTDP, but it
is less effective because of the looser bounds.
Labeling algorithms for time-independent problems
usually keep one label for each extended path. Each
label contains O(1) components that describe the cost
of the path. While solving the time-dependent vehicle
routing problem with time windows (TDVRPTW),
Lera-Romero et al. (2020) observed that the situation is
more complex for resource-dependent problems; dif-
ferent options exists to implement partial dominance,
each having its own strengths and weaknesses. In their
implementation, a simple generalization of the time-
independent model is proposed: for each extended
path, a unique label describing the whole duration
function is kept.
Considering the MTDP from a time-dependent per-
spective provides an interesting insight into how the
representation of labels restricts the techniques that
can be further implemented. The MTDP has been so
far considered within the literature related to time-
independent problems, with no connections to the
TDTSPTW. For instance, note that the algorithm by
Tilk and Irnich (2017) stores one label for each
extended path. Moreover, the duration of each path is
represented by a total function. In this fashion, Tilk
